Author-Name: Timo P. Korkeamaki 
Author-Name: William T. Moore 
Title: Convertible Bond Design and Capital Investment: The Role of Call Provisions 
Abstract:
 If firms issue convertible securities to facilitate sequential investment,
 the securities should be engineered to give sufficient flexibility to
 accommodate timing of follow-on investment. We examine call provisions in
 convertible bonds and argue that firms with investment options expected to
 expire sooner (later) will offer weaker (stronger) call protection. We
 find that issues with weak or no call protection are offered by firms that
 invest greater amounts soon after issuance than those issuing convertibles
 with strong protection. Moreover, capital expenditure levels during the
 5-year period following issuance are inversely related to the length of
 call-protection periods. Copyright 2004 by The American Finance Association. 
